Intel introduced its latest lineup of computer chips on Thursday, headlined by the Gaudi3, an artificial intelligence chip specifically designed for generative AI software. Set to be launched next year, the Gaudi3 aims to rival competing chips from industry giants Nvidia and AMD that currently dominate the landscape of powerful AI models. The announcement signals Intel’s strategic move into the competitive arena of AI processing, attempting to lure AI companies away from the widely adopted Nvidia GPUs that currently power leading models like OpenAI’s ChatGPT.

While Nvidia’s stock has surged nearly 230% year to date, thanks to its stronghold in cloud-based AI with GPUs, Intel, with a 68% rise in shares, is positioning itself to challenge this dominance. The Gaudi3 will enter the market to compete with Nvidia’s H100 and AMD’s upcoming MI300X, aiming to attract AI companies seeking alternatives. Intel’s CEO, Pat Gelsinger, emphasized the significance of generative AI in 2023 and expressed confidence in the Gaudi3’s potential. Alongside this announcement, Intel introduced Core Ultra processors tailored for AI-centric applications, signaling the company’s commitment to making a significant impact on the AI landscape in the coming year.

In addition to the AI-focused chips, Intel unveiled Core Ultra processors designed for Windows laptops and PCs, boasting a specialized AI component called an NPU to accelerate AI tasks. The company also presented fifth-generation Xeon server chips, emphasizing their suitability for AI inferencing, a less power-intensive stage compared to training. These strategic moves underscore Intel’s commitment to adapting to the evolving tech landscape and position itself as a formidable player in the AI chip market.
